e characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Andrew de Atholia Fourth Laird of Glenerochie was born in 1255, in Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Angus de Atholia Third Laird of Glenerochie and daughter of FitzEwen de Atholia. He married Agnes of Glentilt before 1290, in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1355, in Atholl, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 100."},"et":{"1255–1355":"1255–1355","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1270–1355":"1270–1355","1270–1284":"1270–1284","1290–1355":"1290–1355","1180–1